'''Barbara Meislin''' (known as the '''Purple Lady of Tiburon''') is an American author, singer, [[philanthropy|philanthropist]], and healer, known locally in the town of [[Tiburon, California]], for a devotion to things colored [[purple]].
==Biography==
Meislin was born to a single mother in [[Newark, New Jersey]], in approximately 1936.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Jewish News Weekly of Northern California |date=2004-12-10 |title=Tiburon's Purple Lady pens a children's book of many colors |author=Alexandra J. Wall |url=https://www.jweekly.com/2004/12/10/tiburon-s-purple-lady-pens-a-children-s-book-of-many-colors/}}</ref> She trained as a teacher at [[Hunter College]], taught high school and adult education [[French language|French]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]] in Tiburon. After learning guitar as an adult she became an "accomplished" singer,<ref name=burn/><ref name=color/> taught the instrument at [[Dominican University of California|Dominican College]], had a radio show on [[KQED-FM|KQED]] playing [[Music of France|French music]], and played local restaurants, singing in French, Hebrew, and English.<ref name=mij/> She recorded an album of music for healing. She divorced her husband, Jerry Meislin, on amicable terms in 1982.<ref name=mij/>
In October 2009, the large purple house where she had lived for 43 years, a local landmark, burned down.<ref name=burn>{{cite news |title=Tiburon fire destroyed Purple Lady's home |author=Peter Fimrite |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=2009-10-21 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Fire-destroys-home-of-Tiburon-s-Purple-Lady-3213713.php |deadurl=no |accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref>
==Career== She wrote and [[self-publishing|self-published]] a successful book, ''No One Can Ever Steal Your Rainbow'', as well as a song by that name, on the occasion of the death of her daughter, Lori, from a rare childhood virus.<ref name=burn/> The title was taken from a comment by her rabbi, who was consoling her after her purple mailbox was stolen (it was later returned).<ref name=mij>{{cite news |newspaper=Marin Independent Journal |title=Purple Lady hopes book is your rainbow |author=Beth Ashley |date=2005-09-07 |url=http://www.marinij.com/general-news/20050907/beth-ashley-purple-lady-hopes-book-is-your-rainbow}}</ref> The book was later adapted as a ballet that premiered at the Marin Dance Theater.<ref name=color/>
==Public works== Meislin is also known for her charitable work. She is an ardent supporter of [https://web.archive.org/web/20140209225815/http://www.trust-emun.org/ TRUST-Emun - Womens Interfaith Network]; variously founded, and donated the money to build, a hospice library,<ref name=burn/> a "Purple Playground of Friendship" for both Jewish and Palestinian children in [[Neve Shalom|Neve Shalom / Wahat al-Salam]] near [[Latrun]], [[Israel]],<ref name=color/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.jweekly.com/2000/06/23/holy-land-rainbow-park-gives-purple-lady-hope/ |newspaper=Jewish News Weekly of Northern California |date=2000-06-23 |title=Holy Land rainbow park gives 'Purple Lady' hope |author=Aleza Goldsmith}}</ref> a "Positively Purple for the Breast Cancer" fashion show and fundraiser,<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Jewish News Weekly of Northern California |date=1996-11-01 |title='Purple lady' works to create more 'joy in a troubled world' |author=Suzanne Weiss |url=https://www.jweekly.com/1996/11/01/purple-lady-works-to-create-more-joy-in-a-troubled-world/}}</ref> She also donated a [[gazebo]] for a local park<ref name=mij/> and each year, since 2000 she has paid for hundreds of mentors and kids involved in Big Brothers Big Sisters of the North Bay to go ice skating at Snoopy's Home Ice Rink in Santa Rosa, California.
==Purple== Meislin is known for her love for the color purple, and related shades of [[violet (color)|violet]], [[lavender (color)|lavender]], [[Amethyst (color)|amethyst]], [[Lilac (color)|lilac]], [[mauve]], [[magenta]], and [[indigo]].<ref name=color>{{cite news |newspaper=Marin Living |title=The Color Purple: Tiburon's Barbara Meislin finds inspiration in a favorite hue |author=Jim Wood |date=May 2007 |url=http://www.marinmagazine.com/Marin-Magazine/May-2007/The-Color-Purple/ |access-date=2009-10-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025044004/http://www.marinmagazine.com/Marin-Magazine/May-2007/The-Color-Purple/# |archive-date=2009-10-25 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> Most of her possessions are a shade of purple,<ref name=burn/> including among other things: *her make-up *her automobiles (license plates contain the word "Purple") *her cell phone *a garden with purple flowers *her art collection
