{{Infobox academic|honorific_prefix=|name=T. Jack Thompson|honorific_suffix=|native_name=|native_name_lang=|image=File:T. Jack Thompson.jpg|image_size=|alt=|caption=|birth_name=<!-- Use only if different from full/othernames -->|birth_date={{birth date|df=y|1943|2|16}}|birth_place=|death_date={{death date and age|df=y|2017|8|10|1943|2|16}}|death_place=|death_cause=|region=|nationality=|occupation=Scholar of [[Missiologist|missions]]|period=|known_for=History of missions and African Christianity|title=|boards=<!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation   -->|religion=|denomination=<!-- Religious denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->|spouse=Phyllis|children=|awards=<!--Notable national level awards only-->|signature=|signature_size=|signature_alt=|education=|alma_mater=<!-- will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution. -->|thesis_title=|thesis_url=|thesis_year=|doctoral_advisor=|influences=<!--Must be referenced from a third party source-->|era=|discipline=[[Missiology]], [[African Christianity]]|sub_discipline=<!-- Academic discipline specialist area - e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist -->|workplaces=[[Selly Oak Colleges]], [[University of Edinburgh]], [[University of Livingstonia]]|doctoral_students=|notable_students=<!--Only those with WP articles-->|main_interests=|notable_works=|notable_ideas=|influenced=<!--Must be referenced from a third party source-->|website=|footnotes=|movement=<!-- Should match the idiologial movement or denomination (for religious), "school" of thought etc. (e.g. "Anglican", "Postmodernist", "Socialist" or "Green" etc. -->}}
'''T. Jack Thompson''' (16 February 1943 – 10 August 2017) was an Irish [[Missiology|mission historian]] and scholar of [[Christianity in Africa|African Christianity]].

== Biography ==
After studying history at [[Queen's University Belfast]], Thompson taught history and religious education at Regent House School in Newtownards.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Stanley|first=Brian|author-link=Brian Stanley (historian)|date=April 2018|title=In memoriam: Dr T. Jack Thompson (1943–2017)|url=https://www.euppublishing.com/doi/10.3366/swc.2018.0206|journal=Studies in World Christianity|language=en|volume=24|issue=1|pages=82–84|doi=10.3366/swc.2018.0206|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wild-Wood|first=Emma|date=March 2018|title=Obituary: Thomas Jack Thompson (1943–2017)|url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/15733831-12341544|journal=Mission Studies|volume=35|issue=1|pages=4–6|doi=10.1163/15733831-12341544|via=}}</ref> Thompson and his wife Phyllis first travelled to [[Malawi]] as missionaries of the [[Presbyterian Church in Ireland|Presbyterian Church of Ireland]] in 1970. He later developed an academic interest in the study of missions history and Christianity in Africa.

Thompson returned to the United Kingdom and completed his PhD studies at the [[New College, Edinburgh|University of Edinburgh]] in 1980, on the subject of [[Free Church of Scotland (1843–1900)|Free Church of Scotland]] missionary Donald Fraser.<ref name=":1" /> He taught [[Missiology|mission studies]] in the [[Selly Oak Colleges]] in Birmingham, before taking up a post in the 1993 in [[Missiology|mission studies]] at [[New College, Edinburgh|New College]], [[New College, Edinburgh|University of Edinburgh]]. It was in the latter institution that, from 2005 to 2008, he served as the director of the [[Centre for the Study of World Christianity|Centre for the Study of Christianity in the Non-Western World]] and edited the journal ''[[Studies in World Christianity]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Understanding World Christianity: The Vision and Work of Andrew F. Walls|last=Stanley|first=Brian|date=2011|publisher=Orbis Books|isbn=9781608330218|editor-last1=Burrows|editor-first1=William R.|pages=55|chapter=Founding the Centre for the Study of Christianity in the Non-Western World|author-link=Brian Stanley (historian)|editor-last2=Gornik|editor-first2=Mark R.|editor-last3=McLean|editor-first3=Janice A.|via=|}}</ref> During his time in Scotland, he became a leading figure in relations between Scotland and Malawi, including through the [[Scotland Malawi Partnership]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scotland-malawipartnership.org/news-events/all-news/dr-jack-thompson/|title=Dr Jack Thompson|last=Ross|first=Ken|date=14 August 2017|website=Scotland Malawi Partnership|access-date=17 August 2017}}</ref> Ahead of his retirement from the University of Edinburgh, Thompson travelled back to Malawi and was bestowed the [[Ngoni language|Ngoni]] name Jabulani Jere.<ref>{{Cite magazine|year=2008|title=Honours Galore|url=http://www.docs.hss.ed.ac.uk/divinity/Alumni/Bulletin%202008.pdf| magazine=New College Bulletin|page=10}}</ref>

After retiring from Edinburgh, he served a year as Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Livingstonia]] and was later an [[Honorary fellow]] at the University of Edinburgh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/profile/dr-jack-thompson|title=Dr Jack Thompson|date=17 October 2016|publisher=The University of Edinburgh|access-date=28 August 2017|archive-url=https://perma.cc/7X8C-L7SN|archive-date=28 August 2017|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

Thompson died of cancer on 10 August 2017 in the Marie Curie Hospice, Edinburgh, and services were held on 31 August 2017.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cswc.div.ed.ac.uk/2017/08/in-memory-of-dr-t-jack-thompson/|title=In Memory of Dr T. Jack Thompson|last=Stanley|first=Brian|date=11 August 2017|work=Centre for the Study of World Christianity|access-date=11 August 2017|author-link=Brian Stanley (historian)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://announcements.johnstonpress.co.uk/obituaries/scotsman-uk/obituary.aspx?n=thomas-john-thompson-jack&pid=186467614|title=Thomas John (Jack) Thompson's Obituary|date=24 August 2017|website=The Scotsman|access-date=31 August 2017}}</ref>

